		<h2 class='content__hed miller-banner-regular'>Boston Common&rsquo;s oldest trees</h2>

		<p class='content__body'>At 24 Beacon Street, in the northeast corner of Boston Common, a monument honoring Robert Gould Shaw and the Massachusetts Fifty-Fourth Regiment sits between two large, distinctive elm trees. These trees are the oldest English Elms in the Western Hemisphere and are believed to have been planted by John Hancock.</p>

		<p class='content__body'>Documents from 1780 granted permission to plant the elms across from Hancock’s mansion when he was governor. Now encased in a monument to the first African American regiment in the union army, these trees have been dated and are confirmed to have been planted between 1772 and 1812.</p>

		<p class='content__body'>The memorial was erected after the planting of the elms, causing concern at the time that the trees might be damaged or destroyed, but after additional planning and consideration, the work was completed without any injury to the trees, and in fact added beauty to the final tribute.</p>
	</div>

