	<div class='content__container'>
		<h2 class='content__hed miller-banner-regular'>Maintaining a part of history</h2>

		<p class='content__body'>While the Shaw Memorial had undergone several restorations since its unveiling, the two elms were neglected for quite some time over the years. In 1927, it was even thought that the trees wouldn’t be around much longer. However, the genetic potential of the trees is now known to estimate an average lifespan of roughly 300-400 years.</p>

		<p class='content__body'>The location of the elms, their roots restricted and encased by the monument, provides protection against diseases like Dutch Elm Disease. That restriction has also made the wood much denser, keeping insects out.</p>

		<figure class='content__side-img'>
			<img src='/boston-revealed/assets/shaw-elms/bricks.jpg'/>
			<figcaption>
				<p class='content__caption benton-regular'>Bricks were placed inside the tree in order to stabilize the tree trunk.</p>
			</figcaption>
		</figure>
		
		<p class='content__body'>The elms didn’t begin to receive restoration or maintenance of any kind until [1968, check with FG or say “The seventies”], when arborist Henry Davis began overseeing the care of the trees free of charge.</p>
		
		<p class='content__body'>Priorities for keeping veteran trees safe from pests, rot and the ravages of time have meant using some dramatic measures over the years, everything from filling the trees with bricks to lopping several feet off of the tree tops in 2013. To protect the tree and prevent damage to the sculpture, 6 to 8 feet of the tree tops were removed to protect the tree.</p>

		<p class='content__body'>The trees are inspected every [two weeks, checking with FG]. This includes setting compost (leaf mold/organic matter), planting fertilizer every 30 days, soil testing, hydroponic care, monitoring for disease, and retrenchment pruning (cutting heavy or damaged parts of the trees to reduce weight). These maintenance measures keep the trees healthy, maintain growth, strengthen the tree’s exterior, and are what also makes them look strangely amputated over the winter.</p>
	</div>

